60":"about 1360","about 1292":"about 1292","1385":"1385","1261":"1261","1360":"1360","1292":"1292","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1269":"1269","1301":"1301","1322":"1322","1453":"1453","1354":"1354","about 1354":"about 1354","about 1320":"about 1320","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Stafford, Staffordshire, England":"Stafford, Staffordshire, England","Chetwynd, Telford and Wrekin Unitary Authority, Shropshire, England":"Telford, Shropshire, England","Chetwynd, Shropshire, England":"Chetwynd, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Chetwynd","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Chatwin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Chatwin","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Staffordshire): habitational name from a place in Shropshire called Chetwynd, from the Old English personal name <i>Ceatta</i> + Old English <i>(ge)wind</i> ‘winding ascent’."]}]},{"name":"Reginald","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Norman origin, derived from <i>Reginaldus</i>, a Latinized form of   Reynold   influenced by Latin <i>regina</i> ‘queen’. The full form is now regarded as very formal, and bearers generally shorten it to   Reg   in ordinary usage."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":23,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":36,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":45,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Reginald De Chetwynd was born about 1292, in Chetwynd, Shropshire, England, his father, Sir John de Chetwynd, was 33 and his mother, Joan De STAFFORD, was 24. He married Hawisia Vel Avista about 1320, in Chetwynd, Shropshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died about 1360, in his hometown, at the age of 70, and was buried in Telford, Shropshire, England."},"et":{"about 1292–about 1360":"umbes 1292–umbes 1360","1292–1360":"1292–1360","1301–Female":"1301–Surnud","1322–1385":"1322–1385","1261–1354":"1261–1354","1269–1292":"1269–1292","about 1360":"umbes 1360","about 1292":"umbes 1292","1385":"1385","1261":"1261","1360":"1360","1292":"1292","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1269":"1269","1301":"1301","1322":"1322","1453":"1453","1354":"1354","about 1354":"umbes 1354","about 1320":"umbes 1320","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Stafford, Staffordshire, England":"Stafford, Staffordshir